SPECIFIC AIMS. This proposal addresses a gap in our understanding of how
institutions sustain cooperation when the incentives of their members diverge.
The significance of the question is both theoretical and practical: theoretical
because existing accounts treat cooperation as either a product of repeated
interaction or of external enforcement, and practical because the institutions
we care most about operate where neither condition reliably holds. We aim to
test a third account, on which cooperation is sustained by the way an
institution distributes the burden of justification among its members.

BACKGROUND AND SIGNIFICANCE. The dominant models predict that cooperation
unravels as soon as the shadow of the future shortens or enforcement weakens.
Yet we observe durable cooperation in settings that violate both assumptions.
The standard response is to posit norms, but norms invoked this way explain
everything and therefore nothing. Our contribution is to specify a mechanism:
institutions that require members to justify departures from a shared baseline,
to an audience with standing to object, raise the cost of defection without
relying on repeated play or a central enforcer. This reframes a descriptive
puzzle as a question about institutional design.

RESEARCH DESIGN AND METHODS. We will proceed in three studies. The first is
observational: we code a sample of institutions on the strength of their
justification requirements and relate that measure to the durability of
cooperation, controlling for the standard predictors. The second is
experimental: we manipulate the justification requirement in a laboratory
cooperation game and measure its effect on defection. The third is a field
study in which we partner with an organization to introduce a justification
procedure and track outcomes against a comparison unit. Each study addresses a
threat the others leave open; together they triangulate the mechanism.

ANTICIPATED OBJECTIONS. A reviewer may object that justification requirements
are themselves a form of enforcement, collapsing our account into the one it
claims to displace. We disagree: enforcement imposes a cost on the act, while
justification imposes a cost on its public defense, and the two come apart
precisely in the cases we study. A second objection holds that our field study
cannot rule out selection. We address this with the comparison unit and a
pre-registered analysis.

BROADER IMPACTS. If the mechanism holds, it offers a lever for institutional
reform that does not depend on lengthening time horizons or building costly
enforcement, and it bears directly on the design of deliberative bodies.
